number were anew erected, fortified with better pre+tences,
and armed with more unlimited authority<NOTE N="y" PLACE="foot">Clement Walker's hi&s;tory of independency, p. 5. Hollis gives the $word$ repre&s;entation, as Walker, of the plundering, oppre&s;&s;ions, and tyranny of $word$ parliament: Only, in&s;tead of laying the fault on both parties, as Walk$$ does, he a&s;cribes it &s;olely to the independent faction. The pre&s;byterians i$$ deed, being commonly denominated the <HI>moderate</HI> party, would probably $word$ more inoffen&s;ive. See Ru&s;h. vol. vii. p. 598.</NOTE>.</P>
<P>COULD any thing have increa&s;ed the indignatio$
again&s;t that &s;lavery, into which the nation, from the to$
eager pur&s;uit of liberty, had fallen; it mu&s;t have bee$
the reflection on the pretences, by which the people ha$
&s;o long been deluded. The &s;anctified hypocrites, wh$
<PB N="97" REF="141">
called their oppre&s;&s;ions the &s;poiling the Egyptians, and
their rigid &s;everity the dominion of the Elect, interlard|ed
all their iniquities with long and fervent prayers,
&s;aved them&s;elves from blu&s;hing by their pious grimaces,
